From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] drivers/ps4: v37 - shotgun-register ICC at virqs 0..63

Eliminates "0.227 No irq handler for vector" spam by registering
icc_interrupt at MULTIPLE virqs (0..63) with IRQF_SHARED.  Whichever
virq the kernel actually mapped to LAPIC vector 0xE3 (bpcie multi-MSI
base 0xE0 | msg_idx 3 for ICC subfunc 3) catches our handler.

Diagnosis from v30/v34: msi_for_each_desc finds nothing, pci_irq_vector
returns -EINVAL, vector_irq[0xE3]=VECTOR_UNUSED.  We can't find the
correct virq through the standard kernel APIs.  Shotgun is brute force
but reliable.

Spurious failures from request_irq on virqs that don't exist or are
already claimed exclusively are silently ignored.

If v37 works:
- "shotgun-registered ICC at N additional virqs" logs
- "No irq handler for vector" stops appearing
- Real IRQ delivery starts working (icc_interrupt log shows irq != 0)
- Bonus: maybe other bpcie subfuncs also stop spurious-vectoring

---
--- a/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie-icc.c
+++ b/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie-icc.c
@@ -590,6 +590,27 @@
 			sc_err("icc: could not request IRQ: %d\n", ret);
 			goto iounmap;
 		}
+
+		/* v37: shotgun-register icc_interrupt at virqs 0..63 to catch
+		 * whichever the kernel actually mapped to vector 0xE3.  We've
+		 * confirmed the LAPIC fires vector 0xE3 (= bpcie multi-MSI base
+		 * 0xE0 | msg_idx 3) but vector_irq[0xE3] is VECTOR_UNUSED ->
+		 * "No irq handler for vector" spam.  msi_for_each_desc finds
+		 * nothing (per-device MSI domain bypasses standard list).  This
+		 * shotgun ensures whichever virq the kernel allocated for
+		 * msg_idx 3, our handler is on it. */
+		{
+			int v;
+			int registered = 0;
+			for (v = 0; v <= 63; v++) {
+				if (v == icc_virq)
+					continue;	/* already registered above */
+				if (request_irq(v, icc_interrupt, IRQF_SHARED, "icc-shotgun", sc) == 0)
+					registered++;
+			}
+			pr_info("bpcie_icc_init: shotgun-registered ICC at %d additional virqs (0..63)\n",
+				registered);
+		}
 	}
 
 	req_empty = ioread32(REQUEST + BUF_EMPTY);
